 will be as local as possible to where you live.</p>\n\n<p>When you&rsquo;re sent a ‘jury summons’, you must complete and return it within 7 days.</p>\n\n<p>Once your jury service is confirmed, you must turn up on the agreed start date. If you don&rsquo;t, you could be fined £1,000.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Jury service is unpaid but you can claim for food and drink, travel and loss of earnings.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>When you can&rsquo;t do jury service</h2>\n\n<p>There are some situations when you can’t be on a jury - eg if you&rsquo;ve been in prison in the last 10 years. These are listed in the summons.</p>\n\n<h2>How long jury service lasts</h2>\n\n<p>Jury service usually lasts for up to 10 working days - but can be longer.</p>\n\n<p>Many trials last only 2 or 3 days, so you may be on a jury for another trial.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/jury-service/taking-time-off-work","slug":"taking-time-off-work","order":2,"title":"Taking time off work","body":"<p>Give a copy of the letter confirming your jury service to your employer. </p>\n\n<p>Your employer must let you have time off work - however, they can ask you to delay your jury service if your absence will have a serious effect on business.</p>\n\n<h2>Wages during jury service</h2>\n<p>Your employer doesn&rsquo;t have to pay you but you can <a href=\"what-you-can-claim\" title=\"What you can claim for during jury service\">claim for loss of earnings</a> from the court.</p>\n\n<p>Your employer must fill out a Certificate of Loss of Earnings which you get with the letter confirming your jury service. You then send it as part of your claim for expenses once you&rsquo;ve completed jury service.</p>\n\n<h2>Problems with your employer</h2>\n\n<p>You can complain to an <a href=\"/employment-tribunals\" title=\"Employment tribunals\">employment tribunal</a> if you&rsquo;re unreasonably refused time off for jury service.</p>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re sacked because you do jury service y