g","slug":"going-to-a-tribunal-hearing","order":3,"title":"Going to a tribunal hearing","body":"<p>When you go to the tribunal hearing, take your appeal papers and the documents you&rsquo;re using as evidence with you.</p>\n\n<h2>Who will be at the hearing</h2>\n\n<p>The tribunal can be made up of a judge and experts - eg a GP or an accountant (depending on what the case is about).</p>\n\n<p>The department or council may send a representative, known as a &lsquo;presenting officer&rsquo;, to your hearing.</p>\n\n<p>You can bring someone to the hearing to help you - eg a friend, neighbour, relative or someone from an advice centre.</p>\n\n<h2>What happens at the hearing</h2>\n\n<p>The judge and tribunal members will ask you questions about your case.</p>\n\n<p>They will then question anyone you&rsquo;ve brought to the hearing to support your case.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You normally get the tribunal’s decision on the day, but it may be sent in the post a few days after the hearing.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Claiming expenses</h2>\n\n<p>You may be able to claim for expenses for going to the tribunal:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>travelling expenses - the fare on public transport</li>\n  <li>meals - £4.75 if you&rsquo;re away for more than 5 hours, or £9.30 for more than 10 hours</li>\n  <li>loss of earnings - £30.50 if you&rsquo;re away from work for more than 4 hours, or £60.50 for more than 10 hours</li>\n  <li>care expenses (eg for a child-minder) - £5.73 an hour for each child or adult</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The clerk will help you fill in a claim form when you go to the hearing.</p>\n\n<p>Make sure you take receipts, and a letter from your employer for loss of earnings.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>Contact the tribunal as soon as possible if you need to get a taxi, or have to stay away from home overnight.</p>\n</div>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/social-security-child-support-tribunal/if-you-lose-your-appeal","slug":