/www.gov.uk/employment-tribunals/going-to-a-tribunal-hearing","slug":"going-to-a-tribunal-hearing","order":3,"title":"Going to a tribunal hearing","body":"<p>When you go to the tribunal hearing, take the documents you&rsquo;re using to support your case.</p>\n\n<p>You can take a colleague with you if you want, but they can&rsquo;t speak for you or ask questions. You are both entitled to paid time off work for this.</p>\n\n<p>Cases are normally held in the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.justice.gov.uk/tribunals/employment/venues\" title=\"employment tribunal office\">employment tribunal office</a> closest to place where you worked.</p>\n\n<h2>What happens at the hearing</h2>\n\n<p>You (or your representative) and the employer put your cases to a panel or a judge, and answer questions.</p>\n\n<p>You will normally give evidence first, unless your case is about unfair dismissal.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You normally get the tribunal’s decision - or ‘judgment’ - on the day, but it may be sent in the post a few days after the hearing.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>You can&rsquo;t claim for expenses for going to the hearing.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/employment-tribunals/if-you-win-your-case","slug":"if-you-win-your-case","order":4,"title":"If you win your case","body":"<p>If you win your case, the tribunal can order your employer to:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>pay you compensation</li>\n  <li>improve your working conditions</li>\n  <li>give you your job back, if appropriate</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If you are given compensation the amount you get depends on:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>the type of case</li>\n  <li>your age, length of service, and salary</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Usually there are set limits to the amount you can get. However, in cases of discrimination, there is no limit.</p>\n\n<p>If your employer is ordered to re-employ you and doesn&rsquo;t, or fails to obey any other order, the tribunal can force them to pay you extra compensation.</p>\n\n<h2>If your employer doesn&rsquo;t pay</h2>\n\n<p>If you don&rsquo;t get your payment, first contact your employer to find out why. </p>\n\n<p>If they still don&rsquo;t pay, you can force them to.</p>\n\n<p>You may not be able to do this if the employer has, or is about to, appeal.</p>\n\n<h3>If you&rsquo;re in England or Wales</h3>\n\n<p>Ask the local county court to send an enforcement officer to get the money from your employer. This costs £40.</p>\n\n<p>To do this, fill in an <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://hmctsformfinder.justice.gov.uk/HMCTS/GetForm.do?court_forms_id=552\" title=\"N322A - Application to enforce an award form\">application to enforce an award</a> form, using the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://hmctsformfinder.justice.gov.uk/HMCTS/GetForm.do?court_forms_id=552\" title=\"guidance for completing form N322A\">guidance notes</a> to help you.</p>\n\n<p>Send this, with copy of the tribunal&rsquo;s decision, to your <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://hmctscourtfinder.justice.gov.uk/HMCTS/\" title=\"Find your local court\">local county court.</a></p>\n\n<p>You can also use the Fast Track scheme to send a High Court Enforcement Officer - similar to a bailiff - to demand payment from your employer.</p>\n\n<p>This costs £60, which you get back from the employer when they pay.</p>\n\n<p>To use this service, fill in the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://hmctsformfinder.justice.gov.uk/HMCTS/GetLeaflet.do?court_leaflets_id=2393\" title=\"Employment Tribunal Fast Track Enforcement Form\">Employment Tribunal Fast Track Enforcement form.</a></p>\n\n<p>Send it to the address on the form.</p>\n\n<h3>If you&rsquo;re in Scotland</h3>\n\n<p>Write to the office that heard from your case, asking for an &lsquo;extract of the judgement&rsquo;. A Sheriff Officer can use this to force the employer to pay.</p>\n\n<h2>Redundancy payments</h2>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re due a redundancy payment and your employer hasn&rsquo;t paid it, call the Redundancy Payments Helpline.</p>\n\n